  "text": "Cholangiocarcinomas (CCAs) are very aggressive tumors with high mortality due to early intrahepatic invasion and subsequent metastatic spread. The CCAs are classified into 3 subtypes as intrahepatic, extrahepatic, or hilar tumors [1] . The 5-year survival rate is 15% for localized disease and~2% for advanced CCAs with distant metastases, respectively (American Cancer Society). Over the past several decades the incidence of CCAs has been rising in the United States [CITATION_1] . Several potential risk factors have been identified to be associated with the development of CCAs, including age over 65, biliary stones, chronic infection with liver flukes, hepatitis B and C viruses, liver cirrhosis, and primary sclerosing cholangitis [1] . However, the underlying molecular mechanisms involved in CCA development and growth remain elusive.",
